<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-593-489  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 593 489.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  Oct 25 1990 n1237 p18(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>It just takes a bit of understanding. (importance of computereducation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Halton, Colin.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Managers of computer departments and computer users within theirdepartments must have open channels of communication as regardsthe type of equipment being purchased.andP;  Sources within theindustry note that the input of the user is often ignored, andequipment is purchased without their consent.andP;  Some systemanalysts assume that they know what equipment the user wants, andapprove the purchase.andP;  The user knows what the job consists of,and in some cases, the equipment that would be more desirable forthe job at hand.andP;  Employees using the equipment must be involvedin a number of aspects of system development, such as thefeasibility study through implementation and the writing ofmanuals and training.andP;  User's involvement must include the holdingof meetings in their offices and management showing interest inwhatever problems they have.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Employee RelationsUser NeedsTraining of EmployeesEquipment AcquisitionComputer EducationIn-Service TrainingWork Environment.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>